article.headline: Temple 96, Lafayette 73
article.story: PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Temple tuned up for its toughest three-game stretch of the regular season with one of its highest offensive outputs in almost two decades. Dustin Salisbery scored 26 points and Dionte Christmas added 20 as the Owls coasted past Lafayette 96-73 on Thursday night. Mark Tyndale added 20 points off the bench as Temple (6-4) threatened to break the 100-point mark for much of the game. The Owls last reached the century mark in a 110-70 win over Duquense on Feb. 4, 1988. Tyndale's basket gave Temple a 92-64 lead with 6:07 left, but head coach Fran Dunphy began to substitute liberally at that point and the Owls only scored one field goal the rest of the way. "It's pretty meaningless at some point," Dunphy said. "It was more important to get some guys into the game and get them some action." The Owls face Big East power Villanova on Saturday night, travel to No. 5 Duke on Jan. 2, and meet defending Atlantic 10 champion Xavier on Jan. 6. "We've done good work in stretches, and others where we haven't," Dunphy said. "We need to limit our inconsistencies and poor stretches. (Villanova) is a great program and we'll have to play our best." The Owls did set a record for most points in the first half at the Liacouras Center, which opened for the 1997-98 season. They took the lead for good at 14-12 on Dion Dacons' 3-pointer and headed into the break with a 50-37 lead behind 19 points from Salisbery and 13 from Christmas. Marcus Harley had a season-high 23 points for Lafayette (6-8), which lost for just the second time in the last seven games. Harley hit all four of his 3-point attempts in the first half for the Leopards. "Their guys had so much length," said Lafayette coach Fran O'Hanlon, who was Dunphy's assistant at the University of Pennsylvania from 1989-95. "We weren't able to stop them on defense, and even on offense, we had some good looks, but those shots closed up quickly because of their length." The Owls shot 52 percent (29-for-56) from the floor for the game and outrebounded the visitors 44-31.
